MissionCommands.Message: Welcome to Apollo, and Launch Complex 39 here at Cape Canaveral (also known as Cape Kennedy).
You are sitting inside the Apollo Block II Command Module. It is attached to a Service Module where most of the major life support equipment is installed.
The Command and Service Module (CSM) combo is the primary Apollo spacecraft. It is sitting on top of a 363 feet (111 m) high rocket named The Saturn V, whom is currently being prepared for launch.
The CSM is a highly sophisticated spacecraft with both manual and automatic systems that are designed to take you safely to the Moon and back.
To look around, hold down the Mouse Scroll Wheel/middle mouse button and move the mouse. If you reassigned the controls, use your configuration. Try this now.
You can move the camera around inside the cockpit by using the arrow keys. Try to move the camera now.
You can toggle the [V]iew Selector by pressing [V] on the keyboard. Pressing any of the view buttons will move the view/camera towards the selected view point. Try this now.

A flashlight is always available and can be toggled by using [F]. The flashlight will look in the direction of the view, but will also follow the mouse cursor. Try to enable the flashlight and move the mouse cursor around. Then turn it off.
The primary source of power are three Fuel Cells, with batteries installed as backup (or during high power demands).
The Command Module can host three astronauts, each with a primary duty. In this simulator, you assume control of all systems.
The left seat is the commanders seat. Use the [V]iew Menu or press [F5] to set the camera into this seat. Its primary view is the attitude controls, entry monitoring and sequencer control.
The middle seat [F6] is the command module pilot view and has easy access to the computer, environmental control and attitude controls.
The right seat is the Lunar Module pilot [F7] with view of the electrical systems, radio control and SPS engine configuration panel.
There are much more to each seat but this is a general description.

[F9] will move the camera to the left seat window and [F10] will move it to the right seat window. Keep in mind that you can freely move the camera using the arrow keys while holding in the middle mouse button.
The Command Module has a very sophisticated general purpose computer and is seen in the center/left panel. [F11] will move the camera to this view.

Most of the panels and controls are illuminated with both flood lights and fluorescent panel lights controlled from three different panels. Three selectors on Panel 8 controls the commanders numerics, flood and integral lights.
Two selectors on Panel 5 adjust the right side integral and flood lights.
And finally, three selectors on Panel 100 controls the lighting in the Lower Equipment Bay (LEB). This area becomes available for crew use once the seats are stowed.
Each panel is numbered to make it easier to locate switches and controls.
Most of the systems has already been set up for launch but there are a few important steps you need to perform. Using [M], you have access to the MISSION PAD.
From the CHECKLISTS menu on the MISSION PAD, look at the PRE-LAUNCH => LAUNCH PREPARATIONS checklist. It can look quite daunting, but in reality it's quite quick.
I assume you don't touch anything on any of the panels unless you really know what you are doing, almost every switch is functional and will configure a system.
Let us first briefly discuss the computer onboard.
The Apollo Guidance Computer (AGC) is a flight computer hardware system used in both the Apollo Command Module (CM) and Lunar Module (LM) for navigation, guidance, and control.

The Command Module Computer (CMC) is the name for the version of the AGC hardware and software used in the Command Module, distinguishing it from the similar but software-different AGC in the Lunar Module.
In other words, the CMC is one instance of the AGC, while the Lunar Guidance Computer (LGC) is the name of another instance of the AGC installed in the Lunar Module.
The first thing we need to do is to run Program 01 on the Command Module Computer located on MDC-2 (Main Display Console 2 or just Panel 2).
The computer receives input from its keyboard. The keyboard is known as the DSKY, pronounced "dis-key". This stands for Display and Keyboard Assembly, but the term DSKY is commonly used.
The computer is operated by using VERBs and NOUNs. Each is identified with a numeric code.
To run Program 01 on the computer, first press VERB.
To change the program running, you use VERB 37 to enter the program selection mode, then use a NOUN to select what program to run.
As you pressed VERB, the Command Module Computer (CMC) is waiting for input. Click on 3.
Followed by 7.
Then click ENTR to commit the CMC command.
The numerics are showing 37 and flashing, indicating it is waiting for more input. This is the noun. When you pressed ENTR after inserting 37, it automatically knows you will enter a noun next.
Click 0 on the DSKY (keyboard).
Then click 1 on the DSKY.
Then press ENTR once again on the DSKY to commit the CMC command.
Good. The CMC is now showing 01 on the upper right digit, indicating it is running program 01.
Program 01 will align the Inertial System and automatically run Program 02 when ready. While P01 is running the attitude indicator (FDAI) on MDC-1 will roll to the correct launch attitude.

Program 02 will fine align the inertial systems until lift-off. When the rocket detects that it is released from the launchpad, the CMC will receive a signal and automatically run program 11 - the boost program.

Program 11 is critical for the boost phase so, if for some reason, Program 11 won't start, you will do this manually. As we are discussing the CMC, I will explain how now, but this is usually a later step in the BOOST PREPARATION checklist.

A shortcut to do this exists if this is detected, and is done through V75E. Don't press anything yet, but what this means is that you need to press VERB, then 7, then 5, then ENTER to commit the CMC command.
It is very hard to press anything on the console during launch as the vibrations are on the extreme levels. It is therefore important to prepare for this before the countdown.
To do this, you will just before launch enter VERB, then 7 and then 5, but do NOT press ENTER.
If for some reason Program 11 don't start when you are released from the launch pad, all you need to do is to press the ENTR button. We will do this soon.
Now that Program 02 is running on the computer, we can continue with the boost preparations. First thing we do is to distribute the electricity among the 16 Reaction Control System (RCS) thrusters.
Look left on Panel 8. A long horizontal set of switches named the AUTO RCS SELECT switches can be found. This can connect a thruster to either Main Bus A or Main Bus B, or disable it.
These are grouped into what a given thruster is assigned to do. First two groups are all thrusters used for rolling, then the third is for pitch and lastly the forth for yaw.
These switches has three positions. Up connects the jets power to MNA, down to MNB and center sets it to OFF. Verify that A1 is OFF by checking that the switch is in its center position.
Verify that C1 is OFF.
Verify that A2 is OFF.
Verify that C2 is OFF.
Next roll group, set B1 to MNA.
Set D1 to MNB.
Set B2 to MNA.
Set D2 to MNB.
Then the pitch group, set A3 to MNB.
Set C3 to MNA.
Set A4 to MNA.
Set C4 to MNB.
Then the last yaw group, set B3 to MNA.
Set D3 to MNB.
Set B4 to MNB.
And finally, set D4 to MNA.
Let's also check Battery C. Battery C is important and is used for many of the important electrical systems during failures. Rotate the DC selection knob on MDC-3 to BAT C.
The voltage of the selected DC source can be seen in the DC VOLTS gauge. Check that the voltage is 37-37.5 vdc.
Rotate the DC Selector knob to Main Bus A.

A Flight Director & Attitude Indicator (FDAI) is used to see your attitude, errors and rates based on a stable platform. The one on MDC-1 should now display a pitch of 90, yaw of 0 and roll of 90 + the target Azimuth.
Set the FDAI scale to 5/5. This is how sensitive the FDAI will be. We will now verify and enable some maneuvering systems so they are easily useable in-case of an abort.
Verify that the RATE is set to HIGH. This will allow a faster angular rate during manual maneuvering.
Verify that the TRANS CONTR PWR is set to up. This will ensure the translation stick is powered during the ascent.
Set the Rotational Hand Control Direct Power 1 to MNA/MNB.
Set the Rotational Hand Control Direct Power 2 to MNA/MNB.
Verify that the Command Module Computer mode is set to FREE.
Then we will set the BMAGs to RATE 1. The BMAGS are used for backup attitude source, and for angular rates. Set BMAG ROLL to RATE 1.
Set BMAG PITCH to RATE 1.
Set BMAG YAW to RATE 1.
Then we will do an Astro Launch Operations Voice Check. Set the Lunar Module Pilot S BAND switch to OFF.
Set the Commander VHF AM switch to OFF.
Use the COMMUNICATION menu (keyboard button [C]) to do a RADIO CHECK.
Set the Lunar Module Pilot S BAND switch to T/R.
Set the Commander VHF AM switch to T/R.
Then do another RADIO CHECK to check the radio communication with MCCH.
Now ensure the Service Propulsion System engine is set to OFF by first verifying that the SPS THRUST switch on MDC-1 is NORMAL.
Then check that the ΔV THRUST A switch is OFF, still on MDC-1. This switch is hidden behind a protective cover. You can left click on it to OPEN it and right click to close it.
And that the ΔV THRUST B switch is OFF.
Verify the a/PC IND switch on MDC-1 is set to a.
Check that EDS AUTO, 2 ENG OUT and LV RATES on MDC-2 is UP/AUTO. These are systems used to detect an abort. Star by setting EDS to AUTO.
Then verify that 2 ENG OUT is set to AUTO.
And that LV RATES is set to AUTO.
Set the TVC SERVO PWR #1 to AC1/MNA
Set the TVC SERVO PWR #2 to AC2/MNB
Set the Fuel Cell Reaction Valve to LATCH. This will ensure the valve is maintained in the set position even during high vibration phases such as boost.
Verify the secondary coolant loop pump to OFF.
At T -04:10, the 5 L/V ENGINE lights should come on, indicating that they are armed but not thrusting.
Verify that Program 02 is running on the DSKY on MDC-2.
Insert V75 into the computer as discussed earlier, but do NOT press ENTR. You do this by first pressing VERB, followed by 7 and then finally 5. VERB on the DSKY should read 75.

Pull the Primary Glycol to Radiator handle on Panel 325 to bypass. The radiators are warm during the ascent and to avoid the coolant getting heated, we ensure the coolant doesn't flow through the radiators.
Set the Main Bus Tie A/C switch to ON. This will ensure the battery A is connected, sharing the load during ascent.
Set the Main Bus Tie B/C switch to ON. This connects battery B as well. Both battery A and battery B will help the fuel cells with the power demands during ascent and reentry.
Set the PAD COMM switch on the CMP radio panel to OFF.
Set the PAD COMM switch on the LMP radio panel to OFF.
Move out so you can see most of panel 1 and the two FDAIs at the same time, FDAI 1 is on MDC-1 and FDAI 2 is on MDC-2 just above the DSKY.
The Gyro Display Coupler (GDC) stores an inertial platform and is the backup to the primary inertial platform stored in something called the IMU (Inertial Measurement Unit).

The GDC needs to be aligned with the IMU. Tune the view so you can see this GDC align button as well as FDAI 2. Align the GDC by clicking and holding GDC ALIGN pushbutton on MDC-1 down until FDAI 2 stops moving.

The FDAI on MDC-2 should show the same total attitude as the FDAI on MDC-1. FDAI 1 is primarily using the IMU as the data source, while FDAI 2 is using the backup GDC platform as the total attitude source.

The spacecraft should now be set up for launch. As mentioned, the checklist for this can be found in the Mission Pad, one of you primary tools during missions. This concludes the tutorial, good job - I know there are many systems involved so don't stress if you didn't understand most of these yet. Press ESC and End Session to return to the main menu.

Title: Lesson 1 - Pre-Launch
Description:
Welcome to Project Apollo! This spacecraft is far more advanced and complex than both Project Mercury and Project Gemini and will take a lot of studying to master.
These lessons are designed to give you the basic understanding of its systems.
BriefingText:
BRIEFING

Welcome to Project Apollo, the most advanced spacecraft to-date. The spacecraft has many complex systems that work together to provide navigation and life-support for three astronauts for long-duration missions in space.

Don't feel overwhelmed by the amount of switches and systems, it will all make sense in the end. And you will have access to checklists.

This lesson will teach you the final preparations before launch and the boost phase. We will go through the Computer and the systems needed for a safe ascent. However, the mission will end before the launch.
